{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655922"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18691"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18691"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.67,0.19,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11423"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76853"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11423"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62358"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10310"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26452"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26461"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76853"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effects of parasympathetic nervous system activation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased blood glucose and metabolic rate","Decreased pupil diameter and increased digestion","Increased bronchial smooth muscle relaxation","Increased heart rate and blood pressure","Decreased gastrointestinal motility and secretions"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe parasympathetic nervous system causes \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased pupil diameter and increased digestion\u003C/strong\u003E through acetylcholine release at muscarinic receptors. This promotes conservation of energy and digestive functions.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased gastrointestinal motility and secretions\u003C/strong\u003E - Parasympathetic activation increases gut motility and secretions to aid digestion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased heart rate and blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Parasympathetic activation decreases heart rate and has minimal effect on blood pressure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased bronchial smooth muscle relaxation\u003C/strong\u003E - Parasympathetic activation causes bronchial constriction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased blood glucose and metabolic rate\u003C/strong\u003E - These are sympathetic effects; parasympathetic activation reduces metabolic rate\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe parasympathetic nervous system promotes energy conservation and digestive functions through the vagus nerve and sacral outflow, preparing the body for rest, recovery and digestion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The parasympathetic nervous system promotes rest and digest functions through acetylcholine release at muscarinic receptors.","Parasympathetic activation decreases heart rate, increases gut motility, and stimulates digestion.","The vagus nerve is the main parasympathetic nerve, innervating most organs above the pelvis."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"623